[Our thanks to Mahmoud for forwarding this report.

Livestock anthrax is sporadic in Uruguay and thus under-reported. Anthrax has been reported in the departments of Artigas, Cerro Largo, Durazno, Florida, Lavalleja, Paysandu, Rio Negro, Rivera, Rocha, Salto, Soriano, Tacuarembo, and Treinta y Tres. It is essentially a bovine problem, with 7 to 17 outbreaks each year and with occasional outbreaks in horses and swine. Human cases are not infrequent: The frequency of human cases suggests that the disease is significantly under-diagnosed -- why else would a gaucho skin the animal? -- and that vaccination is erratic. The true incidence could well be twice the reported frequency because of being unsuspected and thus under-diagnosed.

While the authorities discourage burning the carcasses, which is the optimum procedure, burial is effective, though subsequent outbreaks can be associated with contaminated gravesites.

Carcass burning can be done safely. For advice and guidance, contact the "Hot Shot" fire control folk in Yellowknife, in Canada's Northwest Territory. They are expert in burning wood bison. For a more effective control and surveillance program, contact the veterinary service staff in either or both North and South Dakota. They will soon have eradicated anthrax in those states.

The persistence of this disease can probably be blamed on its sporadic incidence, poor recognition and reporting, inadequate site disinfection, and ineffective vaccination. When there is good surveillance paired with area annual herd vaccination, the disease disappears. It is eradicable. - Mod.MHJ

